	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				nice post.<BR>
I have some additional tips, that should be familiar to most , but oddily enough strange radical ideas to many many others.<BR>
<BR>
Casters... please wait until agro is established, a good rule is 1/3 of the life. SOW and wolf form can be good for an escape but bad if you are telling your group how much you want that guy pulled off you but you are bouncing around like daffy duck and none of the melee types can even get close enough to hit it. Keep this in mind it happens so much. <BR>
<BR>
My main is a Ranger (are we done making comments, sigh)... please tanks, tough guys and gals, Dont continually hit taunt till you are down to one bubble of health(ive had one or two tell me its just a habbit, well its a bad one) and then wonder what is going on, give me a chance to spread out the damage, believe it or not, im in my mid 30's and self buffed i have over 1000 hit points, my agility is pretty high, meaning that although i get hit, a lot of those hits are not for as much as my warrior companions have been taking. here is an example: The warrior pulls the mob, mob is pounding the warrior each time for 89dmg, the mob is &quot;crunching&quot; the warrior with each hit, pow doubles the warrior for 109, i try my best agro techniques to take the mob away also saying back up for a second to the warrior, *snare even if it has stuck adds a good amount of agro, so cast it again, ignite or stinging swarm, with a round of melee and taunt and a disarm attempt should take the focus to  you, and what do you know this same mob that has been pounding the warrior type for almost 90dmg each time misses me 5 times in a row, then hits for under 20 , still gets a big shot in for 60 perspectively this is big becuase my total hit points , but over all, i have given the warrior a chance to step back up and stay in the fight till the end.<BR>
Damage management can really add to the life of the party and the recovery time.<BR>
Also being that i dont have that many HP as a warrior Healers make sure you have multiple levels of healing prepared for a battle, if i am almost dead a single sup heal will fill me back up. Dont spend that mana on Greater Heals and such, ask your melee types how many HP they have so you know what healing spell will be best to cast upon them at what point, a GH is about 2 and a half bubbles of my life , while for a typical warior of the same level it will be like 1 or 1-1/2.<BR>
Agree entirely with the shaman that say group just pulls away when you arrive, i have a specific set of spells i use for travel that are of course different from combat spells, leaving me without DD, or DOT when i get to group can be frustrating, give me just a few seconds, it could save a bigger amount of down time due to healing or having to mana burn becuase that guy that just got to the group didnt help fill the gap as well as they could of.<BR>
BUFFS, yes they are great, discuss what buffs you have and use them to the groups advantage. This is worth the down time as buffing all your tank type companions may take about half or over of your mana, they last awhile usually, and will save you mana in the long run for heals etc. If you are grouped with a druid and ranger, the ranger should sow everyone, dont let that ranger tell you that he wants to snare(its too cheap mana wise anyway not a valid excuse) or nuke, cmon, you know that whatever nuke i get, i can deal in one simple double attack, save your druids some mana let them do what they do best, you can handle giving out some sow's.<BR>
Im sure i am leaving many things out in my comments but you know the deal, These simple things may take up to an additional 5 minutes to get ready for a pull , but they could save you upwards of 30 minutes searching for a rez or doing a CR. <BR>
Best of luck to you all<BR>
S.Briarwood
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
