	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Well, I hate to be the one to point this out (heh), but in the range mentioned (30-45 outdoor combat), a wizard will handle adds better than an enchanter, primarily because of Bonds of Force (aoe snare and aggro, allowing the wizard to kite around if need be), Steelskin/Diamondskin (allowing them to actually &quot;tank&quot; for a small to medium amount of hitpoints without putting any demands on the healer; 300hp/500hp), and faster casting times.<BR>
If you have both a wizard and an enchanter in your group, they should work *together* to park adds instead of arguing about which *one* of the two should do it--a tiny bit of advance planning will turn up a number of strategies that make dealing with even 2-3 adds easy as pie.  (such as, weak wizard AoE to get aggro, enchanter mass-mez.<BR>
Mobs breaking mez after this will be FAR more likely go after the wizard, who has recast their skin spell by now, and can handle being beaten on for the five to ten seconds it will take for the enchanter to remez.  In this scenario, if the enchanter were doing *only* mass-mezzing, those mobs are going to be all over the enchanter when it ends, making it take considerably longer to quell them.  (The key here being that the wizard is acting as a decoy and preventing the additional mobs from any doing concrete damage, while keeping the enchanter's hands free to do their stuff.  This is also one of those cases where the two can work four times faster than either one individually.  The combination of extra damage from the AoE efficiency more than offsets the expenditure of the skin spell, virtually eliminates the need for the cleric to contribute manna afterwards to either the enchanter gets beaten from missing a mez, or the wizard taking a steady beating from enstilling multiple mobs, and just generally owns when timed properly.  All the enchanter has to do is wait two seconds after they see the wizard start casting to start their mass-mez, and everyone's job gets a whole lot easier.)<BR>
<BR>
One small note: Wizards who have taken the attitude that they should never, ever get touched since level 16 when they got Shieldskin will *not* be able to pull this off as easily as one who has.  Defense and Dodge make a visible difference all the way to just under 50, where most mobs tend to simply squish overly agressive casters under a giant foot.  Typically those skin spells are simply to make it safer for a wizard to ride close to the aggro line, but until mobs start hitting for quad 300's they can be put to other uses as well.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
